I forgot this, and then found it out again. Figured I&rsquo;d just write a small memory fragment here&hellip;
To monitor/watch a Kubernetes object&hellip;
kubectl get pod -w NAME READY STATUS RESTARTS AGE etdofresh-wordpress-7d8ff94558-zfbfl 1/1 Running 0 10h etdofresh-wordpress-mariadb-0 1/1 Running 0 12h ghost-test2-669b4b469-gxw66 1/1 Running 0 5h43m ghost-test2-mariadb-0 1/1 Running 0 5h46m minio-688b86c7c4-qzglp 1/1 Running 0 4m38s And basically it just writes a new line if something happens.

So, i found out something cool today&hellip; when installing minio
helm install minio bitnami/minio I found out via these instructions I can forward a port directly to my local pc.
kubectl port-forward --namespace default svc/minio 9000:9000 Forwarding from 127.0.0.1:9000 -&gt; 9000 Forwarding from [::1]:9000 -&gt; 9000 In browser&hellip;
http://localhost:9000/minio This is my local machine that i am administering from&hellip; I think this may open lots of cool opportunities for accessing the volumes inside&hellip;

